As Dawn rose from her bed beside lord Tithonus\uc0\u8232 bringing light to immortal gods and men alike,\u8232 Zeus sent Strife down to the fast Achaean ship\u8232 the savage goddess, carrying the sign of war.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 She stood by Odysseus\'92 broad-beamed black ship\u8232 in the middle of the line, so she could be heard\u8232 in both directions, from the huts of Ajax,\u8232 son of Telamon, to those of Achilles,\u8232 whose well-balanced ships were drawn up at the ends,\u8232 for these men trusted courage and their own strong hands.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a010\u8232 Standing there, the goddess screamed out a piercing call,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[10]\u8232 a dreadful sound. In the heart of each Achaean,\u8232 she put strength for war, for unremitting combat.\u8232 To men war then became sweeter than sailing back,\u8232 going home in their hollow ships to their dear native land.\u8232 The son of Atreus shouted to his Argives\u8232 to get their armour on. He pulled on his shining bronze.\u8232 First on his legs he set his shin guards\'97beautifully made,\u8232 fitted with silver ankle clasps. Then he put\u8232 a breast plate round his chest, something he\'92d received\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a020\u8232 as a gift of hospitality from Cinyras,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[20]\u8232 who\'92d learned in Cyprus the great news that Achaeans\u8232 were intending to set sail in their ships for Troy.\u8232 So to please the king, Cinyras gave the breastplate\u8232 to Agamemnon. On it were ten metal strips,\u8232 each dark blue, twelve of gold, and twenty made of tin.\u8232 On each side, three enameled snakes coiled to the neck,\u8232 like rainbows which the son of Cronos sets in clouds,\u8232 prophetic omens for mortal men. On his shoulder,\u8232 he slung his sword studded with shining gold.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a030\u8232 The scabbard was silver, fitted with golden straps.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[30]\u8232 Then he picked up his richly decorated shield,\u8232 which covered his whole body, a beautiful work,\u8232 with ten bronze circles, twenty bosses of white tin,\u8232 and in the centre a boss of blue enamel.\u8232 On that shield, as crowning symbol, stood the Gorgon,\u8232 a ferocious face with a horrifying stare.\u8232 Terror and Panic were placed on either side.\u8232 On the shield\'92s silver strap writhed an enamel snake,\u8232 its three heads intertwined, all growing from one neck.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a040\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[40]\u8232 On his head Agamemnon placed his helmet,\u8232 with four bosses, a double ridge, and horsehair plume,\u8232 which nodded menacingly on top. He took two strong spears,\u8232 sharp ones with bronze points, whose glitter shone from him\u8232 right up to heaven. Athena and Hera gave\u8232 peals of thunder overhead, paying tribute to him,\u8232 Agamemnon, king of Mycenae, rich in gold.\
Then each man told his charioteer to curb his horses\uc0\u8232 and line up in good formation at the ditch\'92s edge,\u8232 while they marched ahead on foot in all their armour,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a050\u8232 moving fast, shouting bravely in the early dawn.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[50]\u8232 They arranged their ranks on the far side of the ditch,\u8232 well beyond the chariots following at some distance.\u8232 Then Cronos\'92 son brought them confusing signs of trouble,\u8232 sending down from high in heaven a rain of blood\u8232 dripping from the sky, for his intention was\u8232 to hurl the heads of many brave men down to Hades.\
On the opposite side, by the high ground on the plain,\uc0\u8232 Trojans gathered round Hector, fine Polydamas,\u8232 Aeneas, whom Trojan people honoured like a god,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a060\u8232 and three sons of Antenor\'97Polybus, Agenor,\u8232 godlike man, and youthful Acamas, who seemed\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[60]\u8232 like one of the immortals. In the front ranks,\u8232 Hector carried his shield, an even perfect circle.\u8232 As some ominous star now suddenly appears,\u8232 shining through the clouds, and then disappears again\u8232 into the cloud cover, that\'92s how Hector looked,\u8232 as he showed up in front, then in the rear,\u8232 issuing orders. All in shining bronze, he flashed\u8232 like lightning from Father Zeus, who holds the aegis.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a070\
Then, just as reapers work in some rich man\'92s fields,\uc0\u8232 arranged in rows facing each other, cutting the crop,\u8232 wheat or barley, scything handfuls thick and fast,\u8232 that\'92s how Trojans and Achaeans went at each other,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[70]\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 slicing men down. No one thought of lethal flight.\u8232 The sides were matched in fury equally\'97they fought\u8232 like wolves ripping at each other. Looking on, Strife,\u8232 goddess who brings much sorrow, was delighted.\u8232 She was the only god present at this battle.\u8232 The others were far off, sitting at their ease,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a080\u8232 in their own homes on many-ridged Olympus,\u8232 where a fine house had been built for each of them.\u8232 All blamed the son of Cronos, lord of the dark cloud,\u8232 because he planned to give glory to the Trojans.\u8232 But Father Zeus was not concerned on their account.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[80]\u8232 Withdrawing some distance from them, he sat apart,\u8232 exultant, glorious. He looked out at Troy,\u8232 at the Achaean ships, at the flashing bronze,\u8232 at warriors killing, and at warriors being killed.\
Throughout the early morning, as that sacred day\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a090\uc0\u8232 grew stronger, weapons thrown by both sides\u8232 took their grim toll\'97men kept on falling.\u8232 But at the hour a woodcutter prepares his meal\u8232 in some mountain glade, when his arms are tired\u8232 cutting big trees, when weariness comes in his heart\u8232 and sweet appetite for food overtakes his mind,\u8232 that\'92s when Danaans, calling to each other in the ranks,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[90]\u8232 courageously broke through. The first to kill a man\u8232 was Agamemnon. He slaughtered Bienor,\u8232 shepherd of his people, and his companion, too,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0100\u8232 O\'efleus, the charioteer, who\'92d jumped down\u8232 from the chariot to challenge Agamemnon.\u8232 He\'92d charged straight at him, but his forehead took a blow\u8232 from a sharp spear. The rimmed helmet made of heavy bronze\u8232 didn\'92t stop the spear, which smashed through it, through the bone,\u8232 and splattered his brain inside the entire helmet.\u8232 That stopped his bloodthirsty charge. Agamemnon,\u8232 king of men, stripped off their tunics and left them there,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[100]\u8232 their white skin showing. Then he moved on to butcher\u8232 Isus and Antiphus, two of Priam\'92s sons\'97\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0110\u8232 one was a bastard, the other one legitimate\'97\u8232 both travelling in a single chariot. The bastard,\u8232 Isus, held the reins, and renowned Antiphus\u8232 stood beside him as the fighting man. These two men\u8232 Achilles had once tied up with willow shoots,\u8232 when he\'92d captured them while they were herding sheep\u8232 along Mount Ida\'92s lower slopes. He\'92d let them go\u8232 for ransom. But this time, wide-ruling Agamemnon,\u8232 son of Atreus, with his spear struck Isus in the chest,\u8232 above the nipple, and his sword sliced Antiphus\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0120\u8232 right by his ear, throwing him out of the chariot.\u8232 He quickly stripped off their fine armour. He knew them,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[110]\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 for he\'92d noticed them before by the fast ships,\u8232 when swift-footed Achilles led them in from Ida.\u8232 Just as a lion chews up with ease the tender offspring\u8232 of some nimble deer, when he comes in their den\'97\u8232 his strong teeth seize them and rip out their tender life\'97\u8232 and the mother, even close by, cannot help them,\u8232 for a fearful trembling panic seizes her, so she runs fast,\u8232 bolting in a lather through dense foliage and trees,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0130\u8232 from that mighty beast\'92s attack\'97in just that way,\u8232 no Trojan then could save these two from slaughter,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[120]\u8232 for they were running off in flight from Argives.\
Next, Agamemnon battled brave Hippolochus\uc0\u8232 and Peisander, sons of fiery-hearted Antimachus,\u8232 a man who\'92d received much gold from Alexander,\u8232 a splendid gift, so he\'92d agree not to hand back\u8232 Helen to fair-haired Menelaus. This man had two sons.\u8232 Mighty Agamemnon now caught them, both riding\u8232 in one chariot, attempting to control their horses.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0140\u8232 The shining reins had fallen from the driver\'92s hands,\u8232 panicking the horses. The son of Atreus jumped out\u8232 and faced them like a lion. From the chariot\u8232 the two warriors appealed to Agamemnon:\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[130]\
