a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0270\u8232 grabbed the spear in his fists and yanked it towards him\u8232 with the fury of a lion, pulling it away,\u8232 right out of Iphidamas\'92 hands. Then he hit him,\u8232 his sword slashing through his neck\'97his limbs collapsed,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[240]\u8232 and Iphidamas fell there into a bronze sleep,\u8232 unhappy man, far from the wife he\'92d married,\u8232 to help his fellow citizens, far from that lady\u8232 from whom he\'92d had no favours, though for bride price\u8232 he\'92d offered much. First, he\'92d given a hundred cattle\u8232 and promised a thousand goats and sheep combined,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0280\u8232 taken from the immense numbers in his flocks.\u8232 But then Agamemnon, son of Atreus, killed him,\u8232 stripped him, and went off through the Achaean throng,\u8232 carrying his armour.\
