and sat down on some chairs. Fair-haired Hecamede\uc0\u8232 made them a soothing drink. Old Nestor had taken her\u8232 from Tenedos, when Achilles ransacked the place.\u8232 Daughter of great-hearted Arsinous, she\'92d been chosen\u8232 for him by Achaeans, because he excelled them all\u8232 in giving wise advice. First, she pushed out in front of them\u8232 a well-polished table with feet of blue enamel.\u8232 Then she set there a bronze basket holding onions,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0710\u8232 to spice up their drink, with pale honey and bread\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[630]\u8232 made of sacred barley. Beside these she set a cup,\u8232 a magnificent work Nestor had brought from home,\u8232 studded with gold. There were four handles on it,\u8232 around each one a pair of golden doves was feeding.\u8232 Below were two supports. When that cup was full,\u8232 another man could hardly lift it from the table,\u8232 but, old as he was, Nestor picked it up with ease.\u8232 In this cup Hecamede, looking like a goddess,\u8232 made a soothing drink for them from Pramnian wine.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0720\u8232 In it with a bronze grater she shredded goat\'92s cheese,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[640]\u8232 then shook white barley grain on top. When she\'92d prepared it,\u8232 she invited them to drink. The two men drank\u8232 and quenched their parching thirst. They started talking,\u8232 enjoying each other\'92s pleasant conversation.\u8232 Then Patroclus stood in the doorway, like some god.\u8232 Seeing him, old Nestor leapt up from his shining chair,\u8232 took him by the hand and invited him to sit.\u8232 Patroclus declined, staying where he was. He said:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Old man, divinely bred, I can\'92t sit down.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0730\uc0\u8232 You\'92ll not talk me into it. The man who sent me\u8232 is honourable but quick to take offence.\u8232 I\'92m here to learn the name of that wounded man\u8232 you drove in with. But I see him for myself.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[650]\u8232 I know Machaon, his people\'92s shepherd.\u8232 Now I\'92ll go back and tell this to Achilles.\u8232 You know well enough, divinely bred old man,\u8232 what he\'92s like\'97not someone to take lightly.\u8232 He\'92d be quick to blame an innocent man.\'94\
Geranian horseman Nestor then said to Patroclus:\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0740\
\'93Why is Achilles showing pity now\uc0\u8232 for Achaea\'92s sons, those men hurt with spears\u8232 and arrows? He knows nothing of our trouble,\u8232 the great suffering which afflicts the army.\u8232 For our best men lie injured at the ships,\u8232 crippled by arrows, spears, and swords.\u8232 Strong Diomedes, son of Tydeus, is hurt,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[660]\u8232 as is Odysseus, famous for his spear,\u8232 Agamemnon and Eurypylus as well,\u8232 with an arrow in his thigh. This man here,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0750\u8232 hurt with an arrow from some bowstring,\u8232 I\'92ve just brought in from battle. Achilles is brave,\u8232 but shows no pity, feels nothing for Danaans.\u8232 Is he waiting till our fast ships by the sea\u8232 are set on fire with all-consuming flames,\u8232 and Achaeans, powerless to stop it,\u8232 are slaughtered one by one? My strength now\u8232 in my supple limbs is not what it used to be.\u8232 I wish I were as young, my strength as firm,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[670]\u8232 as when the Eleans and our people\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0760\u8232 went to war for stolen cattle, when I killed\u8232 Itymoneus, brave son of Hypeirochus,\u8232 a man from Elis, as I was driving off\u8232 what we\'92d seized in reparation. He was fighting\u8232 for his cattle. In the foremost ranks,\u8232 a spear from my hand struck him. He collapsed.\u8232 His country people ran away, and so we seized\u8232 a huge amount of plunder from that plain\'97\u8232 fifty herds of cattle, as many flocks of sheep,\u8232 fifty droves of pigs, fifty herds of wandering goats,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0770\u8232 one hundred fifty horses, all chestnut mares,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[680]\u8232 many with foals still standing under them.\u8232 At night we drove these to the citadel\u8232 of Neleus\'92 city, Pylos. Neleus rejoiced,\u8232 glad at heart, because I\'92d shared in so much loot,\u8232 though I was just a young man going to war.\u8232 Next day at dawn, heralds proclaimed out loud\u8232 that all those to whom Elis stood in debt\u8232 should meet together. The leading men of Pylos\u8232 thus gathered to appropriate the spoils,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0780\u8232 for Epeians were in debt to many men.\u8232 Those of us in Pylos were few and weak.\u8232 Mighty Hercules had come some years before\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[690]\u8232 and sapped our strength by killing our best men.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://records.viu.ca/~johnstoi/homer/iliad11.htm#n1"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \strokec2 *}}\uc0\u8232 Neleus once had twelve worthy sons\'97\u8232 I\'92m the only one remaining. The others\u8232 were all wiped out. Bronze-armed Epeians\u8232 at that point took advantage of us,\u8232 committing evil and aggressive acts.\u8232 From that plunder old Neleus selected\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0790\u8232 a herd of cattle, a large flock of sheep,\u8232 taking three hundred of them with their shepherds.\u8232 Holy Elis owed him an enormous debt\'97\u8232 four prize-winning horses with their chariot,\u8232 which had come to Elis to compete, intent\u8232 on racing for a tripod. But Augeias,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[700]\u8232 king of men, kept the horses there in Elis.\u8232 He sent their diver back, grieving for his team.\u8232 Old Neleus was angry with Augeias\u8232 for what he\'92d said and done. That\'92s why he took\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0800\u8232 so much booty for himself. The rest he gave\u8232 to be distributed among the people\u8232 in equal shares, so no one would object.\u8232 We allocated each and every bit\u8232 and sacrificed to all the city gods.\u8232 On the third day Epeians came in force,\u8232 all together, with their sure-footed horses,\u8232 at top speed, lots of them. Among them came\u8232 the two Moliones, fully armed, still young,\u8232 not knowing much of serious warfare.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0810\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[710]\u8232 Now, there\'92s a certain city Thryoessa,\u8232 far off on a steep hill by the Alpheius,\u8232 at the very end of sandy Pylos.\u8232 Desperately eager to destroy this place,\u8232 they pitched their forces round it in a siege.\u8232 But once Epeians crossed the entire plain,\u8232 Athena came speeding from Olympus\u8232 down to us at night. She brought a message\'97\u8232 we should arm ourselves. She mustered a force\u8232 of volunteers in Pylos, all keen for war.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0820\u8232 Neleus would not let me take up arms.\u8232 He hid my horses\'97he thought I was ignorant\u8232 of anything to do with war. But even so,\u8232 though I fought on foot, I made my mark\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[720]\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 among our charioteers. For Athena\u8232 planned the battle out in just that way.\u8232 There is a river Minye\'efus, which meets the sea\u8232 near Arene. The Pylian horsemen\u8232 waited there till dawn while squads of men on foot\u8232 came streaming in. We moved out quickly\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0830\u8232 with our weapons, all together. At noon\u8232 we reached the holy river Alpheius.\u8232 We sacrificed fine beasts to Zeus almighty,\u8232 a bull to Poseidon, and one to Alpheius.\u8232 To Athena with the glittering eyes we offered\u8232 a cow from our own herd. Then we had dinner\u8232 at our positions there throughout the camp.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[730]\u8232 We went to sleep, each man with his weapons,\u8232 along the river bank. The brave Epeians\u8232 were encircling the city, hearts set on razing it.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0840\u8232 Before they managed that, they saw a fight,\u8232 a major battle. For when the sun appeared\u8232 above the earth, we sacrificed to Zeus\u8232 and to Athena, then started our attack.\u8232 When Pylians and Epeians began the battle,\u8232 I was the first to kill a man and seize\u8232 his sure-footed horses. That man was Mulius,\u8232 a spear fighter, son-in-law to Augeias.\u8232 He\'92d taken as his wife fair-haired Agamede,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[740]\u8232 the eldest daughter, who knew all medicines\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0850\u8232 this wide earth provides. As he came against me,\u8232 I struck him with my bronze-tipped spear. He fell\u8232 into the dust. I jumped in his chariot,\u8232 taking my place among the foremost fighters.\u8232 Stout-hearted Epeians saw the man go down,\u8232 leader of their horsemen, their best fighting man.\u8232 They ran away in all directions. I pursued,\u8232 going after them like some black whirlwind.\u8232 I captured fifty chariots. In every one\u8232 two warriors bit the dust, slain by my spear.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0860\u8232 And I\'92d have slaughtered both the Molines,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[750]\u8232 Actor\'92s descendants, but their father,\u8232 the wide-ruling shaker of the earth, Poseidon,\u8232 with a thick concealing mist let them escape.\u8232 Then Zeus put great power into Pylians.\u8232 We pursued Epeians over that wide plain,\u8232 killing them and gathering their fine weapons,\u8232 until we pushed our horses into Bouprasium,\u8232 a wheat-rich region, to the rock of Olene,\u8232 the place which people call Alesium hill.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0870\u8232 There Athena turned our soldiers back.\u8232 I killed the final warrior and left him there.\u8232 Achaeans quickly led their fast horses back\u8232 from Bouprasium to Pylos, all of them\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[760]\u8232 paying tribute among all the gods to Zeus,\u8232 and among all men to Nestor. That\'92s how\u8232 I once used to be, when I was a man\u8232 among the men. But what of Achilles?\u8232 His courage will profit no one but himself.\u8232 I think he might bitterly regret all this,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0880\u8232 once our army is destroyed. O my friend,\u8232 that day Menoetius sent you from Phthia\u8232 in Agamemnon\'92s cause, he gave you orders.\u8232 Both lord Odysseus and myself were present.\u8232 We heard all he said to you there in his house.\u8232 We\'92d come to the well-built home of Peleus,\u8232 mustering men across fertile Achaea.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[770]\u8232 And we found warrior Menoetius and yourself,\u8232 together with Achilles. In the courtyard,\u8232 old horseman Peleus was burning thigh bones\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'